You are a senior React Native, mobile audio, and music-notation engineer. Build a polished, production-quality iOS and Android application named “PoKeyBoard”.

Do not merely provide a plan or sample snippets. Work directly in the repository, implement the app, run the available checks, and leave the project in a buildable state.

If the repository contains an existing standalone HTML piano application, use it as a behavioral and visual reference only. Port its functionality into a native React Native application. Do not wrap the HTML app in a WebView.

# 1. Product goal

PoKeyBoard is a mobile-first piano performance, notation, and recording app.

A user should be able to:

1. Play a realistic-sounding piano using a multi-touch on-screen keyboard.
2. See played notes appear immediately on a musical staff.
3. Use a built-in metronome.
4. Record a performance as editable, structured note-event data rather than microphone audio.
5. Save multiple performances as persistent “takes”.
6. Reopen, rename, duplicate, delete, import, and export takes.
7. Play a take back while seeing:
   - the score follow the playhead;
   - the corresponding piano keys animate;
   - the same piano sound used during live performance.
8. Pause playback and scrub the score in either direction.
9. Hear the notes crossed during score scrubbing, at a cadence that follows the user’s scrolling speed.
10. See the corresponding keyboard keys animate during scrubbing.
11. render a take into compressed, shareable audio;
12. Open the native iOS or Android share sheet so the audio can be shared through WhatsApp, Messages, email, Files, Drive, and other installed apps.

The app must work offline after installation. No account, backend, or cloud service is required for version 1.

# 2. Important terminology

A “take” is the structured performance data: notes, durations, velocities, pedal events, tempo settings, and metadata.

“Recording” normally means capturing piano note events generated inside the app. It does not mean recording from the microphone.

“Audio export” means rendering the structured take through the same piano engine and producing a compressed audio file.

Do not request microphone permission. PoKeyBoard does not need the microphone for its core functionality or audio export.

# 3. Required technology stack

Use the latest mutually compatible stable releases and pin exact versions in the lockfile.

Use:

- React Native with Expo
- TypeScript with strict mode
- Expo Router
- Expo prebuild / Continuous Native Generation
- Custom Expo development builds, not Expo Go
- react-native-audio-api for the real-time and offline audio graph
- @shopify/react-native-skia for musical notation and other performance-sensitive drawing
- react-native-gesture-handler
- react-native-reanimated
- expo-sqlite for persistent takes
- expo-file-system for JSON and audio files
- expo-document-picker for importing take JSON files
- expo-sharing for native file sharing
- expo-keep-awake while recording, playing, or exporting
- zod or an equivalent runtime schema validator for imported JSON
- a lightweight typed state-management solution such as Zustand

Do not use a browser-only Web Audio implementation.

Do not maintain two separate piano engines. Design the audio scheduling code so that both real-time playback and offline audio export use the same sample mapping, envelopes, sustain behavior, reverb settings, velocity mapping, and note scheduling logic.

# 4. Repository and execution rules

Before implementation:

1. Inspect the repository and identify any existing piano logic, assets, branding, or data structures.
2. Preserve useful algorithms where appropriate, but reorganize them into native mobile architecture.
3. Briefly state the implementation plan and intended file structure.
4. Then proceed with implementation without waiting for routine approval.

During implementation:

- Use actual working code, not pseudocode.
- Do not leave TODOs in any core user flow.
- Do not silently replace a difficult requirement with a mock.
- Handle errors visibly and recoverably.
- Run type checking, linting, and tests after meaningful changes.
- Test native audio behavior in both iOS and Android builds where the environment permits.
- Document any limitation that truly cannot be verified in the available environment.

# 5. Application structure

Create three primary areas:

## Play

The main instrument screen containing:

- app/take title;
- save status;
- musical score;
- playhead;
- transport controls;
- recording controls;
- metronome controls;
- piano keyboard;
- sustain control;
- share/export action.

## Takes

A persistent local library showing:

- take title;
- date last edited;
- duration;
- tempo;
- note count;
- optional small score preview.

Actions:

- Open
- Rename
- Duplicate
- Share audio
- Export JSON
- Delete, with confirmation
- Import JSON
- Create new take

Sort takes by most recently edited by default.

## Settings

Include:

- piano volume;
- reverb amount;
- fixed or touch-position velocity;
- fixed velocity value;
- sustain behavior;
- score quantization;
- score zoom;
- scrub audition on/off;
- metronome volume;
- count-in length;
- appearance preference where practical;
- reset settings.

# 6. Mobile-first visual design

Create a premium but approachable visual identity for PoKeyBoard.

Recommended direction:

- warm dark charcoal or walnut surfaces;
- ivory white keys rather than pure white;
- subtle key shadows and depth;
- restrained amber or gold accent color;
- clear red recording state;
- large, thumb-friendly transport controls;
- uncluttered typography;
- high contrast without looking clinical.

Requirements:

- Support portrait and landscape layouts.
- Respect safe areas, notches, and system navigation areas.
- Use a minimum practical touch target of approximately 44–48 logical pixels.
- Avoid a desktop toolbar compressed onto a phone.
- Keep the keyboard large enough to play comfortably.
- In portrait, prioritize score visibility and at least one playable octave.
- In landscape, expand the keyboard and score.
- Support phones and tablets.
- Prevent layout jumps when controls appear or disappear.
- Use subtle animations, but never delay audio in order to synchronize an animation.
- All visual key presses must be driven from the same note-event state used by the audio system.

# 7. Piano keyboard

Implement a multi-touch piano keyboard with at least three logical octaves. A larger configurable range is welcome, but three octaves must be fully supported by the audio and notation engines.

Suggested default range:

- C3 through B5

Requirements:

- Correct white-key and black-key geometry.
- Multi-touch chords.
- Track each touch independently by touch identifier.
- Note-on when a finger enters a key.
- Note-off when that finger leaves or is released.
- Support glissando by moving a held finger across keys.
- Never leave stuck notes after:
  - interrupted gestures;
  - app backgrounding;
  - incoming calls or audio interruptions;
  - navigation;
  - component unmounting;
  - playback stop.
- Black keys must receive hit testing before overlapping white keys.
- Animate a key immediately on note-on.
- Use octave/range shift controls on small screens rather than requiring accidental one-finger panning while playing.
- Do not let a single playing finger unexpectedly scroll the keyboard.
- During playback or score scrubbing, the keyboard may auto-pan to reveal active notes, but it must not auto-pan while the user is actively playing.
- Add optional note labels such as C4.
- Add a visible sustain control that can be latched on mobile.
- Sustain must also be captured as timestamped pedal events in a recording.

Velocity:

- Mobile devices do not provide reliable piano-style key velocity.
- Default to deriving velocity from the vertical position of the initial touch within a key:
  - near the top: softer;
  - near the bottom: stronger.
- Apply a musically sensible nonlinear velocity curve.
- Provide an accessibility setting for fixed velocity.
- Clamp stored velocity to the range 0.0–1.0.

# 8. Realistic piano audio

The final app must be sample-based. Do not ship an oscillator-only piano as the final implementation.

Use a legally redistributable, permissively licensed multi-sampled acoustic grand-piano sample bank.

Asset requirements:

- Include the sample source and license in THIRD_PARTY_NOTICES.md.
- Do not scrape or redistribute unlicensed samples.
- Store a sample-pack version identifier.
- Include at least three useful velocity layers.
- Use multiple root samples across the supported keyboard range.
- Pitch-shift only within a small interval around each root sample.
- Include release behavior and natural decay.
- Release samples are desirable where the chosen sample bank supports them.
- Add a small room or studio reverb using an impulse response or an equivalent efficient effect.
- Let the user control reverb wet/dry mix.
- Keep enough master headroom to avoid clipping.
- Add a gentle limiter or soft-clipping stage if necessary.
- Target at least 32 simultaneous voices; 48 is preferable.
- Implement predictable voice stealing, prioritizing the oldest quiet/releasing voice.
- Reuse decoded AudioBuffers instead of decoding a sample for every note.
- Preload the visible keyboard range first, then complete the remainder.
- Provide an obvious loading state before the instrument is ready.

Audio architecture should expose operations resembling:

- initialize()
- preloadSamplePack()
- noteOn(midi, velocity, source)
- noteOff(midi, source)
- setSustain(down)
- allNotesOff()
- setMasterVolume()
- setReverbMix()
- scheduleNote()
- dispose()

Use a stable audio-context clock for scheduling. Do not use React state updates or raw setTimeout calls as the source of audio timing truth.

# 9. Live musical notation

Use React Native Skia to render an interactive horizontal score.

For version 1, implement a clear, musically correct grand staff rather than attempting a complete professional engraving engine.

Required notation features:

- Treble and bass staff.
- Treble and bass clefs.
- Bar lines and measure numbers.
- Time signature.
- Notes positioned correctly according to MIDI pitch.
- Ledger lines.
- Stems.
- Basic beams or flags for eighth and sixteenth notes.
- Whole, half, quarter, eighth, and sixteenth durations.
- Dots where needed.
- Accidentals for black-key notes.
- Basic rests.
- Chords when notes begin within the same quantization window.
- Current playhead.
- Current or most recently played note name.
- Highlight notes during playback and scrubbing.

Use C major as the default displayed key context. Display accidentals explicitly instead of attempting automatic key-signature inference in version 1.

Split notes between staffs using a sensible middle-C boundary, while allowing ledger lines near the split.

Rendering rules:

- Preserve raw performance timing for playback.
- Quantize only the visual representation unless the user explicitly applies destructive quantization.
- Default visual quantization: nearest sixteenth note.
- Allow visual quantization to be changed to:
  - Off
  - Eighth note
  - Sixteenth note
- Keep note-event audio timing unchanged when display quantization changes.
- Render only visible or near-visible measures for large takes.
- Handle at least 2,000 note events without making scrolling unusable.
- Show an empty staff and a clear prompt when no take exists.

When the user plays without recording:

- Show a temporary “ghost” note on the staff.
- Show its note name.
- Do not permanently modify the current take.

When recording:

- Commit notes to the active take.
- Show them on the score as soon as practical.
- Extend the visible duration while a key remains held.

# 10. Metronome

Implement a built-in, sample-accurate or scheduled-ahead metronome using the audio-context clock.

Features:

- 40–240 BPM
- BPM stepper
- Editable numeric BPM
- Tap tempo
- Time signatures:
  - 2/4
  - 3/4
  - 4/4
  - 6/8
- Accent the first beat of each measure.
- Independent volume.
- Start/stop toggle.
- Visible beat indicators.
- Count-in:
  - Off
  - 1 bar
  - 2 bars
- Store metronome and tempo settings in each take.
- Continue metronome timing accurately while recording.
- Do not rely on an unscheduled JavaScript interval for each click.
- Exclude the metronome from shared audio by default.
- Offer “Include metronome” in the audio-export dialog.

# 11. Recording and transport

Transport controls:

- Return to beginning
- Record
- Play
- Pause
- Stop
- Current time / total duration
- Seek/scrub position
- Optional loop toggle if it can be added without destabilizing core behavior

Recording behavior:

1. Pressing Record arms recording.
2. Apply the configured count-in.
3. Start the recording timeline at beat one after the count-in.
4. Record note-on and note-off timing from the audio-context clock.
5. Capture velocity.
6. Capture sustain events.
7. Stop finalizes all active notes safely.
8. Autosave the take.
9. Provide “Undo last recording pass”.
10. Provide “Clear take” with confirmation.

When recording into a non-empty take, provide a clear mode:

- Overdub from current playhead
- Replace from current playhead

Default to overdub.

Do not destroy existing notes without explicit confirmation.

Playback behavior:

- Schedule notes ahead using the audio-context clock.
- Animate keys at the corresponding scheduled times.
- Highlight score notes.
- Move the playhead smoothly.
- Auto-scroll the score while playing.
- Pause must preserve the current position.
- Resume must continue from that position.
- Stop must release all voices and return to a predictable state.
- Seeking while paused must update the score and keyboard state without starting normal playback.
- Rapid play/pause/stop actions must not create duplicate schedulers.

Use a transport state machine rather than scattered booleans. Example states:

- idle
- countIn
- recording
- playing
- paused
- scrubbing
- exporting

Invalid transitions should be prevented.

# 12. Paused score scrubbing with audible preview

This interaction is a defining feature and must be implemented carefully.

When normal playback is paused or stopped:

- The user can drag the score horizontally.
- The playhead remains visually fixed while the score moves beneath it, or an equivalent direct-manipulation design may be used.
- Convert score position into take time continuously.
- As note onsets cross the playhead, audition those notes.
- Animate the corresponding keyboard keys.
- Forward dragging plays crossed notes in chronological order.
- Backward dragging plays crossed notes in reverse chronological order.
- Slow dragging produces slowly spaced note previews.
- Fast dragging produces rapidly spaced note previews.
- Inertial scrolling should continue auditioning notes while the score continues moving.
- The audible preview should naturally follow actual crossing times rather than playing at one fixed rate.
- Avoid replaying the same onset repeatedly due to tiny finger jitter.
- Use a small hysteresis threshold.
- Clamp preview-note duration to a short useful range so rapid scrubbing does not create an unbounded wall of sustained sound.
- Fade preview voices cleanly when scrubbing stops.
- Sustain from the original take does not need to be fully reconstructed during rapid scrubbing; prioritize intelligible note previews.
- Disable normal transport scheduling during scrubbing.
- Normal playback should resume from the final scrub position.
- Add a setting to turn scrub audition off while preserving silent visual seeking.

Create and unit-test a pure function similar to:

getCrossedNoteOnsets(previousTimeMs, nextTimeMs, notes)

It must:

- return ascending events for forward movement;
- return descending events for backward movement;
- avoid duplicate boundary events;
- handle chords;
- handle large jumps efficiently.

# 13. Canonical take format

Use a versioned JSON format. All times should be integer milliseconds relative to the beginning of the take.

Use a structure based on:

{
  "schemaVersion": 1,
  "id": "uuid",
  "title": "My Take",
  "createdAt": "ISO-8601 timestamp",
  "updatedAt": "ISO-8601 timestamp",
  "durationMs": 12345,
  "samplePackVersion": "grand-piano-v1",
  "tempo": {
    "bpm": 120,
    "timeSignature": {
      "numerator": 4,
      "denominator": 4
    },
    "countInBars": 1
  },
  "instrument": {
    "id": "grand-piano",
    "masterVolume": 0.85,
    "reverbMix": 0.18
  },
  "notes": [
    {
      "id": "uuid",
      "midi": 60,
      "startMs": 0,
      "durationMs": 420,
      "velocity": 0.78
    }
  ],
  "pedalEvents": [
    {
      "atMs": 1000,
      "down": true
    },
    {
      "atMs": 1800,
      "down": false
    }
  ],
  "display": {
    "quantization": "1/16",
    "zoom": 1,
    "playheadMs": 0
  }
}

Rules:

- MIDI note is the canonical pitch representation.
- Derive note names rather than trusting imported note-name strings.
- Sort notes deterministically by startMs, MIDI pitch, and id.
- Reject NaN, negative durations, invalid MIDI values, and velocities outside 0–1.
- Repair minor recoverable import issues where safe.
- Display a useful error for invalid files.
- Preserve unknown forward-compatible metadata where practical.
- Add migrations when the schema changes.
- Imported files with colliding IDs should receive a new local ID unless they are explicitly replacing the same take.

# 14. Persistent take library

Use expo-sqlite.

A practical table may contain:

takes:
- id TEXT PRIMARY KEY
- title TEXT NOT NULL
- created_at TEXT NOT NULL
- updated_at TEXT NOT NULL
- duration_ms INTEGER NOT NULL
- bpm REAL NOT NULL
- note_count INTEGER NOT NULL
- data_json TEXT NOT NULL
- audio_export_uri TEXT NULL
- audio_export_hash TEXT NULL
- is_draft INTEGER NOT NULL DEFAULT 0

Also maintain a metadata/migrations table.

Persistence requirements:

- Database migrations must be idempotent.
- Use transactions for take writes.
- Autosave active changes with a short debounce.
- Force an immediate save when:
  - recording stops;
  - the app backgrounds;
  - a take is closed;
  - the user starts audio export.
- Restore the last open take and playhead after an ordinary restart.
- Keep a recoverable draft when the user has not named or explicitly saved a new take.
- Never lose a completed recording merely because the user navigates away.
- Clean references to missing cached audio files.
- Invalidate an audio-export cache whenever take data or export settings change.

# 15. JSON open, save, import, and export

Implement:

- Import take JSON through the system document picker.
- Export a take as a human-readable JSON file.
- Suggested extension:
  - .pokeyboard.json
  - ordinary .json should also be accepted.
- Use runtime schema validation.
- Show a preview before completing import:
  - title;
  - duration;
  - note count;
  - BPM.
- Provide a clear conflict strategy for duplicate IDs.
- Allow JSON export through the system share sheet.
- Use safe, sanitized file names.
- Include schemaVersion in every exported file.

# 16. Compressed shareable audio

A take must be exportable as a compressed audio file without using the microphone.

Primary output:

- M4A container
- AAC-LC audio
- Stereo
- 44.1 kHz where supported
- Approximately 160 kbps for music
- MIME type: audio/mp4
- File extension: .m4a

Add an export dialog containing:

- Take title
- Estimated duration
- Quality:
  - Shareable: approximately 128 kbps
  - High: approximately 192 kbps
- Include metronome: off by default
- Reverb: use take setting
- Render and Share
- Cancel

Export pipeline:

1. Snapshot and validate the current take.
2. Compute its duration, including note releases and a reverb tail.
3. Create an OfflineAudioContext.
4. Build the same piano graph used by live playback.
5. Load the same sample buffers or equivalent offline buffers.
6. Schedule all notes, envelopes, sustain changes, and optional metronome events.
7. Render to an AudioBuffer.
8. Prevent clipping and leave sensible headroom.
9. Convert the rendered PCM to a temporary WAV or feed it directly to a native encoder.
10. Encode it to AAC-LC in an M4A container.
11. Write the final file to the app cache.
12. Open the iOS/Android system share sheet.
13. Clean temporary intermediate files.
14. Keep the final cached export only while its take hash remains valid.

The live and offline sound must match closely.

Do not:

- record sound through the device microphone;
- use speaker-to-microphone loopback;
- pretend a WAV file is compressed by renaming it;
- use a fake .m4a extension;
- block the interface without feedback during rendering.

Show:

- export progress;
- current stage, such as “Rendering piano” or “Compressing audio”;
- cancellation where technically safe;
- actionable errors;
- success only after a valid playable output file exists.

Native encoding:

First inspect whether the installed audio stack exposes a supported offline-buffer-to-file or graph-to-file encoding route.

If it does not, implement a small local Expo native module for encoding:

- iOS: use AVFoundation APIs to encode PCM or a temporary WAV into AAC-LC/M4A.
- Android: use platform MediaCodec and MediaMuxer to encode AAC into an M4A/MP4 container.
- Expose a small typed TypeScript API.
- Keep this module local to the repository.
- Include native error propagation.
- Avoid introducing FFmpeg solely for this feature unless there is a clearly documented technical reason and its binary size and licensing implications are documented.

Suggested module API:

encodeWavToM4A({
  inputUri,
  outputUri,
  bitrate,
  sampleRate,
  channels
}): Promise<{
  uri: string;
  durationMs: number;
  sizeBytes: number;
}>

Validate the exported file by checking:

- it exists;
- it is not empty;
- duration is plausible;
- extension and container are correct;
- it can be decoded or played back by the app.

Use a filename such as:

PoKeyBoard - My Take.m4a

Use the system share sheet rather than a WhatsApp-specific SDK. Installed compatible apps should appear as normal share targets.

Provide a temporary WAV fallback only as a clearly labeled development/error fallback. Successful compressed M4A export on both iOS and Android is part of the final definition of done.

# 17. Audio-export caching

Compute a deterministic hash from:

- canonical take JSON;
- piano sample-pack version;
- instrument settings;
- metronome inclusion;
- export quality;
- exporter version.

Store:

- audio_export_uri
- audio_export_hash

If the hash still matches and the file exists, offer immediate sharing without rerendering.

When a take changes:

- invalidate its cached export;
- safely delete stale files later;
- do not block the user’s recording interaction on cache cleanup.

# 18. App lifecycle and audio interruptions

Handle:

- app background and foreground;
- audio focus loss;
- phone calls;
- Siri/assistant interruptions;
- headphones or Bluetooth disconnection;
- route changes;
- screen lock where relevant.

Default version-1 behavior:

- Autosave immediately.
- Pause recording or playback safely.
- Release active notes.
- Preserve the playhead.
- Explain what happened when the user returns if an active recording was interrupted.

Background playback is not required for version 1.

Do not add microphone permissions or foreground microphone services.

# 19. Accessibility

Implement:

- VoiceOver and TalkBack labels for all controls.
- State descriptions such as:
  - “Record, inactive”
  - “Metronome, on, 120 beats per minute”
  - “C4 key, pressed”
- Logical focus order.
- Dynamic text sizing where it will not break the keyboard.
- High-contrast active and selected states.
- Do not rely only on color for recording or playback status.
- Reduced-motion support for decorative animation.
- Fixed-velocity option for users who cannot reliably control touch position.
- Large enough controls for one-handed operation.

# 20. Suggested architecture

Organize the project by domain rather than placing everything in one screen.

A reasonable structure:

app/
  _layout.tsx
  index.tsx
  play.tsx
  takes/
    index.tsx
    [id].tsx
  settings.tsx

src/
  audio/
    PianoEngine.ts
    PianoGraphFactory.ts
    SampleBank.ts
    VoiceManager.ts
    TransportScheduler.ts
    MetronomeEngine.ts
    OfflineTakeRenderer.ts
    AudioExportService.ts
